RigidBody

RigidBody moves with physics

The RigidBody node lets you move objects using physics. You apply forces, impulses, and torque to move objects in your scene.

RigidBody handles gravity and collisions out of the box, so you get up and running with minimal coding.

This force-based approach contrasts with a KinematicBody which you move and rotate by hand. Choosing between these two is a tradeoff between precise controls and automated physics.

RigidBody is incredibly versatile. You can use it for bouncing grenades, push-able blocks, destructible terrain, and much more.

In this guide, you will learn how to:

  • Create a 3D platforming player controller with RigidBody.
  • Push bodies with forces in an explosion.
  • Simulate gravity and collisions.
  • Shatter crates into shards with physics.

Setting up a RigidBody

In Godot, physics nodes need a CollisionShape or CollisionPolygon as a child to define their collider.

This is also true of Area, KinematicBody, and StaticBody.

The collision shape lets them figure out when they are touching or overlapping other bodies.

You need three components for a RigidBody to work:

  1. The RigidBody node, which handles forces applied to itself.
  2. One or more CollisionShape or CollisionPolygon nodes that define the collider of the RigidBody.
  3. Each CollisionShape has a collision shape like a BoxShape or a collider based on a mesh, like a ConcavePolygonShape. Alternatively, a CollisionPolygon has an array of points and an extrude Depth.

You also need to add a mesh to make the RigidBody visible: this is usually a MeshInstance, but you could also use a CSGMesh.

You can also enable Visible Collision Shapes in the Debug dropdown menu to see the colliders when testing the game.

RigidBody key features

The RigidBody has many properties that control how it should react to forces. A lot of its setup involves tweaking physics properties in the editor.

Forces and impulses

You control motion on rigid bodies with force and impulse functions:

  • add_force() sets a force that continuously applies to the body every frame. Think of something like an engine propelling a ship forward or gravity pulling a body down (note that Godot adds gravity to rigid bodies by default).
  • add_impulse() helps you register impacts. It’s a force applied only once when calling the function: for example, the impact of an explosion or a projectile hitting something.

Applying forces and impulses

You can apply a force with add_central_force() or add_force().

A central force only moves a body from its center of mass, while add_force() lets you move the body from any local position.

The node may rotate if you offset the force from its center of mass with add_force().

To apply an impulse, you want to call apply_central_impulse() or apply_impulse(). They work the same as force-related methods, except they apply for one frame.

Note: Applying impulses every frame makes your force framerate-dependent. If the player’s framerate goes down, your bodies’ motions slow down too.

That’s why you only want to use those methods for one-time impulses, like explosions.

Alternatively, you can multiply your impulse by the time since the last physics update when overriding the _integrate_forces() virtual method. The function provides a state.step value: the time interval between two physics ticks.

You’ll see below how we use state.step in concrete use cases.

Applying rotational forces

While the add_force() and apply_impulse() methods can cause a body to rotate on top of moving, you may want only to apply a rotational force. We apply rotational forces with torque.

You can use torque for many effects, like turning a wheel or making a body look at another.

To apply constant torque, use the add_torque() method. For a one-time rotational impulse, you’ll use apply_torque_impulse() instead.

Integrating forces

Unlike other bodies, you don’t want to directly change the position of a RigidBody inside _physics_process(). To combine your motion with the physics engine, you need to use its state.

To do so, you want to override and use the _integrate_forces() virtual function. This function contains a PhysicsDirectBodyState object called state. You can call functions on this object or access variables like linear_velocity to get the body’s speed.

Accessing properties using this state ensures they are up to date following collisions, forces, and impulses.

You’ll see some examples in this guide.

The RigidBody’s four modes

A RigidBody has four modes that change its general behavior:

  • By default, a RigidBody uses the Rigid mode. In this mode, gravity affects the body, and it pushes other bodies during collisions.
  • The Static mode makes your RigidBody completely stationary. It is useful when enabling and disabling doors, locking objects in place.
  • The Character mode is ideal for player characters. It behaves similarly to Rigid mode but won’t rotate on its own. This mode ensures a player’s character remains upright.
  • Finally, Kinematic is a helpful mode for manually making changes to a body. This mode makes the RigidBody work similarly to a KinematicBody: it doesn’t integrate forces, and you have to change its position manually. Use it to take manual control over a character, or in cases where you need to teleport the body to a precise location.

You can control the active mode using the node’s Mode property.

You can switch mode on the fly depending on your needs. For instance, a character can go from the Character mode to Rigid when dying, causing it to get pushed around by other bodies.

Mass, weight, and gravity scale

These three properties greatly affect how a RigidBody moves:

  1. Mass represents how hard to move the object is.
    • The higher the value, the more force you need to move it.
    • The lower the value, the easier it is to move.
    • The body’s center of mass is at the node’s origin.
  2. Weight is Mass multiplied by the Default Gravity, so updating the mass updates its weight in turn.
  3. Default Gravity is a project-wide setting.
    • The physics engine applies it to every RigidBody to make them move down towards the ground.
    • You can change it by going to Project Settings -> Physics -> 3D -> Default Gravity.

Godot’s default gravity is low, set to 9.8: a number similar to acceleration due to gravity on earth.

If you want objects to fall faster, you need to increase this in project settings. You can also increase the gravity scale on your RigidBody itself.

Note that Mass and Weight do not affect the speed at which an object falls.

This relationship is the same as the real world: all objects fall at the same speed. See the hammer and feather experiment on the Moon.

You either need to increase gravity or apply an extra downwards force to make an object fall faster. We’ll see how to apply forces in the examples below.

Reporting contacts

RigidBody has four convenient signals to detect and react when it touches something.

The main two are body_entered and body_exited. The signals work similarly to Area’s signals: the callback tells you what you hit when a collision happens.

You can use them to trigger an explosion when touching a mine, to inflict damage, and more.

By default, rigid bodies don’t report collisions and points of contact for performance reasons. If the collisions happen, the node won’t emit signals.

If you want the node to emit these signals, there are two steps:

  1. Turn on Contact Monitor to get collision reports.
  2. Increase Contacts Reported to the number of contacts you want to support. Once the node emits this number of signals, it ignores the rest in that frame.

As a rule of thumb, you can set contacts reported relatively high if you are dealing with one object.

If you have many objects detecting collisions, you want to limit the reported contacts for performance.

You’ll have to play with the Contacts Reported property in your game to see what works for you.

Physics materials

Physics materials let you fine-tune how rigid bodies interact with each other.

You can save a PhysicsMaterial as a resource and assign it to any RigidBody’s Physics Material Override to reuse it.

The properties you can control are Friction, Rough, Bounce, and Absorbent:

  • Friction determines how much an object slows when colliding with another. It can be useful to set Friction low on a player character; otherwise, they move slower on the floor due to gravity.
  • Rough is a toggle that determines how bodies with different frictions interact. If a body is rough, both colliding bodies use the highest friction. In short, this lets you slow down objects that collide with this body.
  • Bounce determines momentum lost in each collision. With 0 Bounce, an object stops immediately. A Bounce of 1.0 means the body changes direction instead of losing momentum. Think of a basketball hitting the floor versus wet tissue paper.
  • Absorbent is a toggle that determines how bodies with different Bounce interact. The engine subtracts the Bounce of the Absorbent body from the colliding body. In short, a bouncy object colliding with an absorbent body bounces less.

How to use a RigidBody in practice

Making a 3D platforming player controller

Many games take advantage of rigid player characters with physics: pinball machines, birds in Angry Birds, and worms in Worms.

Rigid physics are ideal for games where you want to crash into lots of objects in your world.

Here, you’ll see how to create a 3D platforming game character that walks and jumps with a RigidBody.

Making a player with a RigidBody is convenient as Godot handles gravity automatically. We couldn’t recommend it for all platformers, but using a RigidBody over a KinematicBody can be very helpful.

You can use a RigidBody in the Character mode for a platform game controller.

In this example, we use a Physics Material Override without any friction to stop gravity slowing your movement down as the physics engine pushes you into the floor.

Contacts Reported determines how many collisions Godot pays attention to per frame. If this number isn’t high enough, we can miss collisions with the floor. We need them to know that the character is on the floor and can jump.

For a platforming character in a game with curved terrain or slopes, you can set this number to at least 3 or 4.

You can then use the _integrate_forces() virtual function to apply impulses or forces based on the player’s inputs.

func _integrate_forces(state: PhysicsDirectBodyState) -> void:
    if _should_reset:
        state.transform.origin = _start_position
        _should_reset = false

    _move_direction = _get_camera_oriented_input()

    # To not orient quickly to the last input, we save a last strong direction,
    # this also ensures a good normalized value for the rotation basis.
    if _move_direction.length() > 0.2:
        _last_strong_direction = _move_direction.normalized()

    _orient_character_to_direction(_last_strong_direction, state.step)

    if is_jumping(state):
        _model.jump()
        apply_central_impulse(Vector3.UP * jump_initial_impulse)
    elif is_air_boosting(state):
        add_central_force(Vector3.UP * jump_additional_force)

    add_central_force(_move_direction * move_speed)

The _get_camera_oriented_input() and _orient_character_to_direction() functions are identical to the ones we use in KinematicBody to manage 3D cameras and character rotation.

func _get_camera_oriented_input() -> Vector3:
    var input_left_right := (
        Input.get_action_strength("move_right")
        - Input.get_action_strength("move_left")
    )
    var input_forward_back := (
        Input.get_action_strength("move_down")
        - Input.get_action_strength("move_up")
    )

    var raw_input = Vector2(input_left_right, input_forward_back)

    var input := Vector3.ZERO
    # This ensures correct analogue input strength in any direction with a joypad stick
    input.x = raw_input.x * sqrt(1.0 - raw_input.y * raw_input.y / 2.0)
    input.z = raw_input.y * sqrt(1.0 - raw_input.x * raw_input.x / 2.0)

    input = _camera_controller.global_transform.basis.xform(input)
    return input

func _orient_character_to_direction(direction: Vector3, delta: float) -> void:
    var left_axis := Vector3.UP.cross(direction)
    var rotation_basis := Basis(left_axis, Vector3.UP, direction).get_rotation_quat()
    var model_scale := _model.transform.basis.get_scale()
    _model.transform.basis = Basis(_model.transform.basis.get_rotation_quat().slerp(rotation_basis, delta * rotation_speed)).scaled(
        model_scale
    )

As RigidBody doesn’t have a convenient is_on_floor() function, unlike KinematicBody, we need to code it ourselves.

func is_on_floor(state: PhysicsDirectBodyState) -> bool:
    # Contacts_reported needs to be high enough to count all surfaces on body
    for contact in state.get_contact_count():
        var contact_normal = state.get_contact_local_normal(contact)
        # If the contact is below us we are on the floor
        if contact_normal.dot(Vector3.UP) > 0.5:
            return true
    return false

Make an explosion with forces

Your scenes feel more interactive if the world reacts to big forces like explosions.

When making an explosion, you want objects and rubble to blast away from the origin. RigidBody nodes are great for this as you can apply explosive impulses to them.

In this example, we instance a grenade, which is itself a RigidBody. It contains an explosion particle system and an Area node to determine the radius of the blast.

We use an animation to time the grenade’s explosion.

The animation calls the _explode() function after 1.5 seconds, then removes the instance with queue_free() after another second.

The _explode() function hides the grenade model, starts the particle system, and applies the physics force of the explosion to objects within the ExplosionRadius Area.

func _explode() -> void:
    _model.hide()
    _explosion.set_as_toplevel(true)
    _explosion.emitting = true

    var colliders = _explosion_area.get_overlapping_bodies()
    for body in colliders:
        if body is RigidBody:
            var direction := global_transform.origin.direction_to(body.global_transform.origin)
            body.apply_central_impulse(blast_impulse * direction)

Creating structures that collapse and fall over

Many games benefit from objects that react to physics. Be it boxes you push around, pressure plates, destructible terrain, or walls collapsing.

Here, we cover the example of a scene with a tower that you can knock over with a cannonball.

Clicking fires a projectile. If the projectile touches the tower with the right trajectory, it can knock over its supports.

With RigidBody, you get that functionality almost for free. Make both your cannonball and the structure use rigid bodies.

The cannonball has no logic; it’s just a RigidBody. The cannon, on the other hand, needs to spawn and fire the projectiles.

We capture mouse input in two variables _yaw_input and _tilt_input in the _unhandled_input() function.

func _unhandled_input(event: InputEvent) -> void:
    if Input.get_mouse_mode() == Input.MOUSE_MODE_CAPTURED:
        if event is InputEventMouseMotion:
            _yaw_input = -event.relative.x * mouse_sensitivity
            _tilt_input = -event.relative.y * mouse_sensitivity

We then rotate the cannon based on the input while clamping the rotation to limit the cannon’s movement.

    rotate_y(_yaw_input * rotation_speed * delta)
    rotation_degrees.y = clamp(rotation_degrees.y, yaw_lower_limit, yaw_upper_limit)

    _tilt_pivot.rotate_x(_tilt_input * tilt_speed * delta)
    _tilt_pivot.rotation_degrees.x = clamp(
        _tilt_pivot.rotation_degrees.x, tilt_lower_limit, tilt_upper_limit
    )

Suppose the player presses a specific button and our firing rate timer is not running. In that case, we instantiate a cannonball and set it as top level so it moves independently from its parent. Then we can apply an impulse in the direction the cannon is pointing.

    if Input.is_action_just_pressed("shoot_3d") and _timer.is_stopped():
        _timer.start()
        var cannon_ball: RigidBody = cannon_ball_scene.instance()
        _launch_point.add_child(cannon_ball)
        cannon_ball.set_as_toplevel(true)
        cannon_ball.apply_central_impulse(-_launch_point.global_transform.basis.z * cannon_power)

For the structure, you want to create individual rigid bodies with a collision shape and place them in the editor.

These objects have many properties that let you fine-tune their behavior:

  • The higher their Mass, the more velocity the cannonball needs to knock them down.
  • If you want your bodies to fall faster, you can increase their Gravity Scale or add an applied force downwards via code.

For the cannonball, you can add a Physics Material to get access to more properties. Like Bounce and Friction.

If your objects are rolling around too much, increase their Angular Damping property. This property is beneficial for circular bodies that tend to roll easily.

Turning bodies into debris with a pre-shattered model

Sometimes you might want to have an object explode into tiny pieces and collide with physics—shattered glass, a splintering crate, or an enemy exploding into giblets.

Here, we have a crate shatter into shards when clicked. The fragments tumble about, interacting with each other and the environment.

This effect looks complicated but is actually a simple trick. The crates are RigidBody nodes. On breaking, a shattered version of the crate, made up of many smaller RigidBody nodes, replaces the original.

The shattered box is made using Blender and imported as a glTF file. Using the -rigid suffix on each shard causes Godot to import each shard as a RigidBody with a generated ConvexPolygonShape CollisionShape. Read more about import suffixes here. You can easily add the suffix to multiple objects in Blender using the Batch Rename function in Blender.

The shattered box scene also includes an AnimationPlayer that makes the shards blink for four seconds, then calls queue_free() to remove the shards. Removing the shards helps with performance.

export var shattered_crate_scene: PackedScene

func shatter() -> void:
    var shattered_crate: Spatial = shattered_crate_scene.instance()
    get_parent().add_child(shattered_crate)
    shattered_crate.global_transform = global_transform
    queue_free()

Your questions

When should I use a RigidBody over a KinematicBody?

Rigid bodies are great for many different game objects: ropes, fluids, traps, jump pads, motors, simple enemies, and much more.

Consider using a RigidBody if your player exerts forces on or is forced by other bodies.

They are also popular for mobile games, as you can have lots happening with simple inputs. This is known as emergent gameplay: simple rules causing complex behaviors.

How can I make something float?

Using Gravity Scale, you can make any object float with ease. The Gravity Scale is a multiplier for the default gravity applied to a body. You can increase it to make a body fall faster.

Setting Gravity Scale to 0.0 makes an object float in place as no gravity acts on the body. You can take this a step further and put the Gravity Scale to -1.0.

A negative Gravity Scale makes an object fall upwards instead of falling to the ground, creating things like balloons. As this negative gravity exerts a force, you can use a pin joint to exert upwards on other bodies.

What is sleeping?

When a body is asleep, it acts as a static body. Being asleep means the _integrate_forces() function doesn’t run until a collision or code applies a force. Sleeping is useful for reducing function calls if you have many rigid bodies.

The Can Sleep, and Sleeping properties determine when a RigidBody goes to sleep. You can set the Sleeping property manually; it tells us if the body is asleep. The Can Sleep property tells us if the physics engine can automatically update the value of Sleeping after a duration at rest with no active forces.

The Can Sleep property updates Sleeping with the physics engine. Rigid bodies have the sleeping_state_changed signal for notifying you when the sleeping state of a body has changed.

Note: A body set to Character mode never goes to sleep automatically, but you can still set it manually.

Can I scale my rigid body?

Don’t scale your rigid bodies! Instead, change the size of the shape directly.

Collision shapes easily break when you change their scale dynamically. Changing the scale of a physics body doesn’t apply any forces and leads to unexpected behavior.

If you want to change the scale of a PhysicsBody, you should access the size values of your shape directly.

Another option is to create multiple collision shapes for a body and disable those not at the current size, enabling shapes and scaling the mesh instances separately.

Unexpected behavior can occur when changing the size of a body in too small a space. It is worth using one or more RayCast to detect if your body has enough space to expand.
